<DATELINE>ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists using a robot diver to
explore two War of 1812-era wrecks let schoolchildren across North
America in on the expedition.
   The underwater look Monday at the merchant schooner Hamilton and
its sister ship, the Scourge, was televised live to 13 museums.
Four youngsters watching got to operate the robot using a computer
joystick hooked up by satellite.
   The cold, fresh water of Lake Ontario and the 300-foot depth of
the wrecks helped preserve the two ships, which were pressed into
battle service by the United States during the War of 1812.
   Cannons, railings and an elegantly carved figurehead could be
seen as the black-and-white television image panned slowly.
   Robert D. Ballard, the expedition's leader, and other scientists
gave a running narration and took questions from viewers at the
museums in the United States and Canada and at the Canadian
Football Hall of Fame in Hamilton, a city 25 miles west of St.
Catharines that has title to the wrecks.
   ``The ship is in immaculate condition. We can see the caulking
in the planks,'' Ballard said. ``There's no suggestion that they
suffered any damage due to the sinking itself. They just got
flooded and went down very gently.''
   The Hamilton and the Scourge sank during a storm Aug. 8, 1813,
killing 53 sailors. They had taken part in several battles against
British forces in southern Canada.
   However, the wrecks narrowly escaped damage from large ships
that dragged their anchors across the lake bottom, Ballard said. He
said the furrows caused by the anchors were plainly visible near
the wrecks.
   The wrecks remained undisturbed six miles off St. Catharines, 30
miles south of Toronto on the lake's southern shore, until their
discovery in 1975. Since then, scientists such as French underwater
explorer Jacques Cousteau have used submarines and remote cameras
to explore them, but Ballard's expedition was the most
technologically sophisticated yet.
   In an interview by ship-to-shore telephone, Ballard said the
children's participation was the most significant part of the
program. He said the remote control setup had never been used
before.
   Ballard said the two-week expedition would produce a detailed
map of the wrecks that Hamilton officials could use in deciding
whether to raise them someday.
   Ballard, director of the Center for Marine Exploration at the
Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution in Massachusetts, led the 1985
expedition that discovered the wreck of the Titanic. The storied
ocean liner sank in the North Atlantic after ramming an iceberg in
1912.
   The museums taking part in the program were in Boston; Chicago;
Dallas; Detroit; Memphis, Tenn.; Minneapolis; Rochester, N.Y.; Salt
Lake City; Sarasota, Fla.; Toronto; Victoria, British Columbia;
Washington; and Woods Hole, Mass.
</TEXT>
