<HEAD>Oceanographer Robert Ballard New Host of `Explorer'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underwater scientist Robert D. Ballard is
becoming host of ``National Geographic Explorer'' on SuperStation
TBS because he says the movie and television image of scientists is
driving young people away from science careers.
   ``We're going to change the show's emphasis to more live
exploration,'' said Ballard, the man who found the Titanic and the
Bismarck and recently led an expedition to a sunken Roman ship. That
effort was telecast live to several hundred thousand youngsters in
12 museums across the country.
   His discovery of the Nazi battleship Bismarck, resting upright in
15,000 feet of water about 600 miles west of Brest, France, will be
shown in an October episode of the weekly ``Explorer'' series. The
fabled World War II ship was sunk in a battle with British naval
forces on May 27, 1941. Ballard found the ship June 8.
   ``I want to motivate children and show them that science is a
contact sport,'' said Ballard, who will become host in September.
``We've created an image that scientists are nerds. And that's
created a devastating effect on interest in science as a career.
   ``The battle for children's minds is between grades four to 12.
Right now 50 percent of all the students in American colleges
studying sciences are foreign students. We're now 17th in the world
in science literacy, behind Spain, Hungary and Ireland and
hopelessly behind Germany, Japan, England and the Scandinavian
countries.''
   He warned that if more American students don't become interested
in science the United States will slip economically, industrially
and militarily.
   ``The image children have of scientists is that of a harebrained,
forgetful wacko that they get from movies like `Back to the
Future,''' said Ballard. ``Children want to fit in with their peer
groups, they don't want to look like some silly guy.''
   Ballard is more in the mold of Indiana Jones. He has participated
in or led more than 60 deep-sea expeditions. He is a senior
scientist in the Ocean Engineering Department of the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution, head of the Deep Submergence Laboratory
and director of the institution's Center for Marine Exploration.
   The 50,000-ton Bismarck was the biggest battleship launched by a
European power and was such a threat to the Allies that British
Prime Minister Winston Churchill ordered an all-out effort to ``sink
the Bismarck.''
   The Bismarck sank the British battle cruiser Hood on May 24,
1941, but two days later British torpedo planes damaged the ship's
steering gear and rudders. The crucial battle came the next day.
   ``The Germans lost their main guns and control in the battle,''
said Ballard. ``The captain ordered the ship scuttled at 10 o'clock.
She was equipped with the latest in military technology and he
didn't want the ship captured. The ship was struck by more torpedoes
at 10:36 and sank three minutes later. Of 2,200 crewmen aboard the
Bismarck, only about 115 survived.
   ``The ship capsized and its gun turrets, which were held in place
by their weight, fell out. She landed upright and other than the
missing turrets and some superstructure damage she is in remarkable
condition. The Nazi swastikas are still visible on her deck.''
   The Bismarck was examined by the deep-sea robot Argo, which
Ballard also used to find the Titanic four years ago. The robot is
equipped with sonar, video cameras and still cameras. Pictures taken
by Argo, its tender and the mother ship on the surface will be used
in the ``Explorer'' program in October.
   The Jason Project in the Mediterranean Sea explored a 3rd Century
Roman ship and undersea volcanoes. Six one-hour shows of the
exploration were sent live by satellite to 12 museums in a two-week
period. Each museum had an exact replica of the control facilities
aboard the other ship so that the youngsters saw exactly what
Ballard saw only one-half second later.
   Future live television projects will take Ballard to the Great
Lakes to look for two ships sunk in the War of 1812, to Lake
Champlain to look for a gunboat sunk in the Revolutionary War, to
the Pacific off Okinawa to explore the Japanese battleship Yamata
and to the Pacific to examine the Japanese aircraft carriers that
attacked Pearl Harbor and were sunk in the Battle of Midway.
   ``We have a large program of exploration lined up and will have
the continued involvement of young people,'' Ballard said. ``We'll
take some children into the field, but most will participate by
telepresence. It will almost be like being there because they will
be surrounded by video pictures. On the Great Lakes project we will
have joy sticks in the museums that will let the youngsters actually
control the robot.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   CHALLENGER MOVIE _ A three-hour ABC film re-creating events
leading up to the tragic launch of the Space Shuttle Challenger is
now in production in Houston. Seven astronauts died in the explosion
moments after launch at Cape Canaveral, Fla., on Jan. 28, 1986.
</TEXT>
