<HEAD>Titanic Discoverers to Hold Undersea Classroom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FALMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discoverers of the sunken Titanic
announced a venture Wednesday designed to bring undersea exploration
of a Roman shipwreck to thousands of students across the country via
live television.
   Robert Ballard, who led the team that found the Titanic in 1985,
said students, linked by satellite to at least nine science museums
in the United States and Canada, will be able to communicate with
explorers directing an unmanned mobile camera as it combs the
Mediterranean Sea floor.
   While the $6 million, privately funded project involves several
advances in technology, Ballard said its main purpose is to excite
students about science.
   ``We really have a crisis of education in the United States,''
Ballard said at a news conference at the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution. In recent years, he said, science has failed to provide
young, impressionable students with attractive role models.
   Instead, he said, the role models are ``that scientists are
nerds, or as my kids would say, dweebs, and dweebs sit at terminals
and are dropouts from society.''
   In the ``Jason Project,'' named after the underwater robot that
helped explore the Titanic, high-quality television cable will be
connected to a ship thousands of feet above on the sea surface. For
14 days next May, the ship and its 50-member crew, including six
high school students, will control the movements of the robot and
send back satellite images from two underwater locations.
   In addition, the National Georgraphic Society plans to produce
and broadcast a later special on the expedition.
   The live broadcasts will be transmitted via the Turner
Broadcasting System in Atlanta and Electronic Data Systems Corp. in
Atlanta to the nine science museums in Boston, Chicago, Memphis,
Washington, D.C., Dallas, Philadelphia, Rochester, N.Y., Charlotte,
N.C., and Victoria, British Columbia. The shipboard crew will
broadcast six programs a day or 84 40-minute programs in all that
will be seen by a total of roughly 200,000 students.
   Instead of simply sitting and watching the programs, the students
will have before them a multiscreen control room that replicates the
control center on the ship. Students will be able to ask questions
of the crew and in some cases take over the controls of Jason,
Ballard said.
   Ballard called the concept ``telepresence.''
   The plan is for Jason to explore an undersea volcano field off
the west coast of Italy where minor eruptions, emissions of molten
minerals and an abundance of wildlife will be visible. At another
western Mediterranean site, which Ballard declined to disclose,
Jason will send back pictures of a vast debris field believed to be
the remains of several Roman shipwrecks from the second century, A.D.
   Frank Ireton of the National Science Teachers Association, which
is helping train science teachers who will bring their classes to
the programs, said, ``It's a tremendous interest-generator. If we
have 200,000 students and we interest 10 percent of them in science,
my gosh, that's a tremendous benefit.''
</TEXT>
