<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Nathaniel Wyeth</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nathaniel Wyeth, the brother of artist
Andrew Wyeth and the inventor of the plastic soda bottle, died
Wednesday at age 78.
   The cause of death was not disclosed.
   Wyeth was best known for developing the polyethylene
terephthalate, or PET, bottle, in the early 1970s. The bottle is
used for carbonated beverages, wine, liquor and food because of its
light weight and impact resistance.
   It was patented in 1973, and more than 6 million are produced
annually around the world.
   He began his career at Du Pont Co. in 1936 in the Wilmington,
Del., company's engineering department. Wyeth held numerous other
positions before being named the company's first engineering fellow
in 1963. In 1975, he was named as the first senior engineering
fellow, the company's highest technical position.
   Wyeth invented 25 processes and products that spanned a wide
range, including plastics, textile fibers, electronics and
mechanical systems.
   He is survived by his wife, Jean, five sons, his brother, three
sisters, three stepsons and a stepdaughter.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Harold Hirsch</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold S. Hirsch, who founded White Stag
Manufacturing Co. and was a prominent Portland civic leader and
philanthropist, died Wednesday from cancer at age 82.
   In 1929, Hirsch used a corner of his family's Hirsch-Weis Co.
factory and a couple of its sewing machines to begin making apparel
for downhill skiing.
   His venture grew into a division of his family's company and
became known as White Stag. He is a member of the U.S. Ski Hall of
Fame.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Hirsch also headed a National Alliance of Businessmen's program
to spur the hiring of minority workers and worked with Reed
College, the University of Oregon and Dartmouth College.
   He is survived bu his wife of 41 years, Elizabeth; a son; a
daughter; a stepson; a stepdaughter; a sister, and four
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Frank Casado</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Casado, a restaurateur and activist who
managed to draw politicians and celebrities to a homey eatery
called Lucy's El Adobe Cafe, died Thursday of congestive heart
failure at age 66.
   Casado and his wife, Lucy, purchased a one-room storefront
restaurant across the street from the old Paramount Studios complex
in 1964. Soon they were feeding the famous and the soon-to-be
famous.
   A co-founder of the Mexican American Political Association,
Casado hosted frequent meetings among Mexican American activists
and politicians at Lucy's.
   Former Gov. Edmund G. Brown Jr. was a regular at the restaurant
and appointed Casado to the South Coast Regional Coastline
Commission.
   As an adviser and fund-raiser for various politicians, Casado
briefly considered running for mayor against Tom Bradley.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Susan Tate King</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHPORT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Tate King, who used her radio show
that aired opposite ``Tokyo Rose'' to try to encourage U.S.
servicemen in World War II, died Sunday at age 75.
   The cause of death was not disclosed.
   For 18 months during the war, she played opposite ``Tokyo
Rose,'' with a radio show aimed at boosting the morale of U.S.
servicemen in the Pacific while the Japanese announcer tried to
discourage them.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Walter Rhodes</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKINGHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter ``Lightning Bug'' Rhodes, who
once played guitar for Wilson Pickett and had recently begun a
comeback tour, was found dead Wednesday in a motel swimming pool at
age 50.
   Rhodes was just 6 when he began playing guitar. Besides Pickett,
he performed with such soul and blues stars as Joe Tex, Otis
Redding and B.B. King. His own hits include ``Strollie Bun'' in
1958 and ``It's Not What You Do'' in 1971.
   Rhodes and his band performed in May at the New Orleans Jazz and
Heritage Festival and were to play a concert in September at
Lincoln Center in New York. Also in the works were concerts in
Switzerland and an album featuring 10 of Rhodes' songs, due for
release in the fall.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Paul Wynne</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Wynne, a television news reporter who
turned the camera on himself and his battle with AIDS in the highly
acclaimed ``Paul Wynne's Journal,'' died Thursday of the disease at
age 46.
   Wynne hosted the weekly show that began airing in January.
   ``Paul Wynne's Journal'' gained notoriety as a straightforward,
lively show that won a local Friends of the Human Rights Commission
Award in June.
   A broadcast specialist in the Army, he left in 1969 and came to
San Francisco to work as a press agent for KGO.
   He worked for KQED-TV as an arts critic from 1972 to 1975, then
moved to KPIX-TV where he was an entertainment contributor for
``Evening Magazine'' from 1976 to 1981.
   Wynne moderated a weekly public affairs program for young people
at KPIX, and hosted the Emmy Award-winning children's special
``Comin' at Ya'' in 1979.
   He returned to KGO in 1981, and worked as an entertainment
reporter until 1984.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ruth Becker Blanchard</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Becker Blanchard, who survived
the Titanic disaster as a 12-year-old passenger, died Friday at age
90.
   Blanchard died of the complications of old age, said Don Lynch,
a spokesman for the Titanic Historical Society of Indian Orchard,
Mass.
   Twelve-year-old Ruth Becker was asleep when the Titanic struck
an iceberg on April 14, 1912. She was one of 705 survivors from the
ship that carried about 2,200 people.
   She married, moved to Kansas and raised three children before
teaching grade school in Benton Harbor, Mich. for 20 years. She
retired to California.
   Blanchard refrained from any ocean voyages following the Titanic
disaster until March of this year, when she went on a cruise to
Mexico.
</TEXT>
